{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492995"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1200"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1200"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.11,0.33,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72497"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1200"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57967"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45158"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72497"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one day history of increasing epigastric pain. On the basis of a grossly elevated serum lipase, a diagnosis of acute pancreatitis is made. He is a heavy drinker and this is his third admission in six months with pancreatitis. An assessment must be made of his likely prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most suggestive of a poor outcome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A Ranson score of 5","A Glasgow prognostic criteria score of 2","An APACHE II score of 4","A neutrophil-lymphocyte ratio of 1:1","A Balthazar score of 2"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of different scoring systems for assessing the severity of acute pancreatitis and perhaps the best validated is the Apache score. The Ranson scoring system is reliable, but is limited in that it is valid only 48 hours after presentation. Of the numbers provided in the options, the Ranson score of 5 is the one that suggests a poor outcome. The scores provided by the other systems are more indicative of a relatively mild episode of pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERanson score:\u003C/strong\u003E Calculated on admission and 48 hours later, Ranson score consists of 11 parameters. Mortality increases with increasing score. A score of 6 and above confers a 40% risk of mortality. \u003Cbr /\u003EParameters on admission include WBC, patient age, glucose, AST and LDH. Parameters 48 hours after admission include HCT, BUN, calcium, arterial pO2, HCO3, and fluid requirement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlasgow prognostic criteria:\u003C/strong\u003E Measures blood parameters which are scored 48 hours after admission. A score of 3 would suggest severe pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAPACHE II:\u003C/strong\u003E Measures severity based on physiological parameters, previous health status and age (total of 17 parameters). Can be used during the first 48 hours, during which increasing measurements confers increased risk of severity. This is useful as it can be used within the first 48 hours, but is quite cumbersome to measure. An Apache II score of 8 would suggest severe disease with an 11%- 18% mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophil-lymphocyte ratio:\u003C/strong\u003E A component of poor outcomes in severe pancreatitis is thought to be the result of uncontrolled systemic inflammatory response. The neutrophil to lymphocyte ratio is more useful in this setting than white blood cell count alone. This is calculated by number of neutrophils divided by number of lymphocytes. In acute physiological stress, such as infection or inflammation, neutrophil number increases whilst lymphocyte number decreases, raising the ratio.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBalthazar:\u003C/strong\u003E Used to score the severity of pancreatitis based on CT imaging:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA normal appearing pancreas\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EB enlargement of pancreas\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC inflammatory changes in pancreas and peri-pancreatic fat\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ED ill-defined single peri-pancreatic fluid collection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EE two or more poorly defined peri-pancreatic fluid collections\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ranson score is useful for assessing and communicating pancreatitis severity."],"references":["Venkatesh NR, Vijayakumar C, Balasubramaniyan G, et al. Comparison of different scoring systems in predicting the severity of acute pancreatitis: a prospective observational study. Cureus. 2020;12(2). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32190494/","Vege SS, Whitcomb DC, Ginsburg CH. Predicting the severity of acute pancreatitis. Available at: http://www. uptodate. com/contents/predicting-the-severity-of-acutepancreatitis. 2011."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57967"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1200"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57967"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T21:19:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T20:18:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1200"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72497"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"}